## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| **Critical** | 6 |
| **High** | 0 |
| **Medium** | 2 |
| **Low** | 1 |

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called — achieving ~95% line coverage — but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if the production code is completely broken (e.g., `ApplyBulkDiscount` doubles prices, `Search` returns wrong results, `ImportFromCsv` silently corrupts data).

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching — Systematic No-Assertion Pattern

**The entire class** follows the pattern: call a method, discard or ignore the result. This is the root cause of your "95% coverage, still buggy" problem.

---

#### 2. `AddProduct_Works` (line 17) — No Assertion

```csharp
// BEFORE – proves nothing
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// AFTER – verify the product is actually stored
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
```

---

#### 3. `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 31) — No Assertion

Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price actually changed.

```csharp
// AFTER
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

---

#### 4. `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39) — No Assertion

Never verifies the product is gone.

```csharp
// AFTER
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

---

#### 5. `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63) — No Assertion

Doesn't even capture the return value in a meaningful way.

```csharp
// AFTER
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();
Assert.AreEqual(1, count);
```

---

#### 6. `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 69) — No Assertion

This is the most dangerous one. A 10% discount on $9.99 should yield $8.991, but the test will pass even if the code *increases* prices.

```csharp
// AFTER
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
```

---

#### 7. `ImportFromCsv_Works` (line 85) — No Assertion

Imports data but never checks it was parsed correctly. Malformed CSV parsing bugs will go undetected.

